Next up Vibe Coding with GitHub Copilot
    Getting started. 
    3 modes: Agent, Ask, Plan. These are new since this video was prepared in April 2025. They were Ask, Edit, Agent. Everything is changing so fast!

    I asked Github copilot to create a presentation in black & white on my github repo:
        I'm giving a presentation on my github repo at https://github.com/prentrodgers/One-footed-bride-tuning and I'd like to create some fancy black and white presentation charts covering the technology of tuning, Harry Partch's Tonality Diamond, Simulated Annealing on 4-note chords, the harmony and tuning of JS Bach, Csound sample based synthesis, and the music I've created synthesizing these tools.
    It's building all kinds of charts, flow charts, block diagrams, all very official. He's using Mermaid diagrams. They are not very useful here. I can't use this. Don't give up yet. Ask him to figure something out. He's thinking. I set the model to Auto, and also added the Granite4 from my local Ollama instance. But I can't tell if it will use it in Copilot. 
    She's covering inline coding feature now. She says to press ctrl-i to pull up Copilot inline. But for me it starts up Continue. I'm going to disable continue for a while. 
    It works now. 
    Edit Mode (Now called Agent mode) - natural language prompts and voice. She illustrates by creating a calculator app. 
    She stresses the importance of putting in the chat the files that you want Copilot to work on with the @ sign. 
    Ask mode for asking for help, but not allowing touching any of your files.
    You can include all the code in the current directory by
    1. click paper clip icon --> Add Context or ctrl-/
    2. Select Codebase - doesn't work for me. 

    Inline code completion. ctrl-i opens a tiny window inside your code where you can create a targetted update to the code from a prompt.

    Agents can autonomousely execute multi-step tasks, coding or otherwise. 
    
    Advanced Copilot tools. 
    Context Tools. How to focus Copilot on the files or tools that you want it to use. 
    Slash commands. Open up chat --> Ask and press the slash command to direct Copilot to the right type of task for it to perform. 
    Custom instructions - Provide organization specific preferences for how it does tasks. Can be json or markdown, but must be in specific places and names. 
    For json, ctrl-shift p search for vscode workspace settings. In the root of the repo, it creates a  .vscode directory with settings.json file in it, with an empty set {}.
    For Markdown, create .github folder. Inside that create copilot-instructions.md file with instructions there. For example:
        The first line should be a brief summary under 50 characters. 
        Leave a blank line.
        The body should explain the change in detail, no more than 100 characters, Always begin the commit message with a relevant emoji
    Then put a link in the settings.json to that markdown directory. 
        {
        "github.copilot.chat.commitMessageGeneration.instructions" [
        : { "file": ".github/copilot-instructions.md" }
        ]
        }